# 🎙️ Qnnect — AI-Powered Mock Interview System

**Built With:** TypeScript | React | Vite | Tailwind CSS | Drizzle ORM | Node.js

**Qnnect** is a modern, full-stack AI mock interview platform engineered to bridge the gap between interview preparation and real-world performance. By simulating authentic technical, system design, and behavioral interview rounds, Qnnect provides candidates with an immersive, browser-based environment to practice responses, receive real-time AI evaluation, and build confidence through actionable feedback.

---

## ✨ Comprehensive Feature Set

*   **🤖 Intelligent Question Generation:** Dynamically creates tailored interview questions based on specific job descriptions, target roles, required tech stacks, and user experience levels.
*   **💬 Interactive Mock Sessions:** Simulates realistic, multi-turn interview conversations with context-aware AI prompts and adaptive follow-up questions.
*   **📊 Real-Time Performance Analytics:** Instantly evaluates candidate answers, generating automated scores and granular feedback on communication clarity, technical accuracy, and structural delivery.
*   **🎯 Role-Specific Practice Rounds:** Supports customized interview tracks including Full-Stack Development, Frontend/Backend specialization, System Design, and Behavioral/HR rounds.
*   **🎨 Premium UI/UX:** Designed with a clean, accessible, and distraction-free interface built using React, Tailwind CSS, and custom components.
*   **🛡️ End-to-End Type Safety:** Utilizes TypeScript across both client and server layers, with shared data schemas ensuring robust validation and seamless API communication.

---

## 🛠️ Technology Stack & Architecture

Qnnect is built using a modern Client-Server architecture, optimized for performance, scalability, and developer experience.

| Layer | Technology | Description |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Frontend Framework** | React + Vite | Blazing-fast Single Page Application (SPA) with instant hot-module replacement (vite.config.ts). |
| **Language** | TypeScript | Strong typing across the entire codebase for enhanced code reliability (tsconfig.json). |
| **Styling & UI** | Tailwind CSS | Utility-first CSS framework for responsive, accessible design (tailwind.config.ts, postcss.config.js). |
| **Backend Server** | Node.js / Express | Robust REST API and AI integration server, configured to run on **Port 5003** (server directory). |
| **Database ORM** | Drizzle ORM | Lightweight, high-performance TypeScript ORM for schema and query management (drizzle.config.ts). |
| **Data Validation** | Zod / Shared Schemas | Unified type definitions and runtime validation models shared between client and server (shared directory). |
| **AI Engine** | LLM API Integration | Connects with advanced LLMs to power conversation logic and response grading. |

---

## 📂 Repository File Tree

```text
Qnnect/
├── .local/                 # Local development environment configurations
├── client/                 # Frontend React application (Vite + Tailwind CSS)
│   ├── src/                # UI components, pages, hooks, and routing logic
│   └── index.html          # Main HTML entry point
├── migrations/             # SQL database migration files managed by Drizzle ORM
├── server/                 # Backend Node.js API server (runs on port 5003)
│   ├── index.ts            # Server entry point and middleware setup
│   └── routes.ts           # API endpoints and AI service integrations
├── shared/                 # Shared TypeScript schemas, types, and data models
│   └── schema.ts           # Drizzle database schemas and Zod validation types
├── .gitignore              # Files and directories ignored by Git
├── .replit                 # Replit cloud workspace configuration
├── DEPLOYMENT_NOTES.md     # Production deployment instructions and environment rules
├── components.json         # Custom UI component library configuration
├── design_guidelines.md    # UI/UX styling principles, color palettes, and layout rules
├── drizzle.config.ts       # Database connection and Drizzle migration configuration
├── package-lock.json       # Dependency version lockfile
├── package.json            # Project scripts, metadata, and npm dependencies
├── postcss.config.js       # PostCSS processor configuration for Tailwind CSS
├── replit.md               # Documentation and workspace notes for Replit
├── tailwind.config.ts      # Tailwind design system and theme configuration
├── tsconfig.json           # Global TypeScript compiler options
└── vite.config.ts          # Vite bundler, proxy, and build configuration

```
## 🚀 Step-by-Step Setup & Installation
Follow these instructions to set up your local development environment and run **Qnnect** from scratch.
### 1. Prerequisites
Ensure you have the following installed on your system:
 * Node.js (v18.0.0 or higher recommended)
 * npm or yarn package manager
 * A SQL Database (PostgreSQL recommended for Drizzle ORM compatibility)
 * An active API key from your AI provider (e.g., OpenAI API key)
### 2. Clone the Repository
Open your terminal and clone the project to your local machine using your specific repository link:
```bash
git clone <Your-GitHub-Repository-URL>
cd Qnnect

```
### 3. Install Dependencies
Install all required frontend and backend packages:
```bash
npm install

```
### 4. Configure Environment Variables
Create a new file named .env in the root directory of the project and populate it with your specific configuration details:
```env
# Application Server Port (Default is 5003 as per server configuration)
PORT=5003

# Database Connection String
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://username:password@localhost:5432/qnnect_db

# AI Provider API Key
OPENAI_API_KEY=your_actual_openai_api_key_here

```
### 5. Initialize & Migrate the Database
Push the shared Drizzle schema to your connected database to generate the required tables:
```bash
npm run db:push

```
*(Note: If you need to generate new migration files after modifying schema.ts, use npx drizzle-kit generate before pushing).*
### 6. Launch the Development Environment
Start both the Node.js backend server (Port 5003) and the Vite frontend development server concurrently:
```bash
npm run dev

```
Once initialized, open your web browser and navigate to the local client URL provided in your terminal output (typically localhost port 5173). The Vite development server is configured to proxy API requests directly to your backend running on port 5003.
## 🎨 Design Philosophy & UI Guidelines
Qnnect is built around a user-centric design philosophy detailed in the design guidelines document:
 * **Visual Hierarchy:** Clean typography and distinct contrast ratios ensure that interview questions and AI feedback are readable and scannable.
 * **Responsive Layouts:** Built collaboratively with Tailwind CSS grids and flexbox, ensuring seamless functionality across desktops, tablets, and mobile devices.
 * **Component Modularity:** Reusable UI components maintain visual consistency across dashboard analytics, interview chat rooms, and settings pages.
## 🌐 Deployment Guidelines
When transitioning Qnnect from local development to production, adhere to the following best practices:
 * **Environment Variables:** Ensure your Database URL, AI API Key, and Port are securely configured in your cloud provider's dashboard.
 * **Build Command:** Generate the optimized static frontend build using:
   ```bash
   npm run build
   
   ```
 * **Production Start:** Serve the production build and initialize the API server:
   ```bash
   npm run start
   
   ```
 * **Replit Cloud Hosting:** The project contains pre-configured Replit files. When importing into Replit, ensure your Nix channel and PostgreSQL add-on are active, and provision your secrets in the Replit environment panel.
